In 2012, Northwest Vista College (NVC) was awarded a 3-year NSF grant: Improving Opportunities in Nanotechnology (Project ION #1205010) to increase the number of technicians with 21st century knowledge and skills entering the nanotechnology workforce. To accomplish this goal, the project focused on testing and evaluating new curricula, hands-on laboratory experiments, summer institute programs, professional development for high school and community college faculty, and remote instruction.  In addition, Project ION focused on community outreach and awareness of nanotechnology through the development of cutting edge classroom activities, internship opportunities, memorandum of agreements with potential employers, and career placement&mdash;with an additional aim of determining best practices for pursuing the development of a future ATE Projects grant.

Over the past 3 years, project leadership successfully created a foundation of proven best practices; enhanced NVCÆs inter-connected networks of support and resource sharing among the formal education system, research and development organizations, and industry, and piloted a robust high school and community college faculty professional development program.  These activities helped NVC to generate new interest in high-tech STEM disciplines. In addition, these activities have prepared educators to integrate Nanotechnology into classrooms, and plan for regional and statewide expansion of our education program.  A summary of accomplishments and activities delineating the impact of Project ION include:

Program Development and Improvement

A formal 10 member San Antonio Nanotechnology Forum (SANTF) Committee was established in the greater San Antonio area.
154 students participated in Remote Access laboratory project that was piloted through NACK center at local high schools/districts; 
20 high school students attended in the week-long Summer Nanotechnology Institute; 
Six students participated in hands-on research and project based internship program with Southwest Research Institute; 
Over 200 High School students visited Nanotechnology Table during College and Career Fest at Southwest Independent School District (ISD); 
46 student members joined a Nanotechnology Club that was established at Southwest high school; 
300 students participated in Nanotechnology Day at Natalie High school; 
50 students visited Nanotechnology table during Career Day at Holmes high school; 
Three NVC students were selected to attend NanoJapan Program that was hosted by Rice University as part of a NSF grant; 
Two NVC students were accepted into the National Nanotechnology Infrastructure Network (NNIN) Research Experience for Undergraduates Program; 
Five students earned a Student Award for Excellence by the NSF at Annual ATE PI Conference; 
Mentoring and partnership opportunities were utilized from two existing ATE Centers to develop Project ION as the first phase of a program that engages high school students and educators in nanotechnology learning activities; 


Professional Development for Educators

15 high school and community college STEM faculty participated in the week-long summer "Educate the Educators" workshop in 2013, in which 11 faculty Cohort returned subsequent year in 2014.
14 high school and community college faculty participated in a Remote Access workshop.
Nanotechnology Teaching and Learning kits developed by NCLT center at Northwestern University and SCEM center at University of New Mexico were distributed to 10 local high schools and 1 sister college. Teachers implemented the teaching materials to their classrooms, workshops, and STEM event that yields 1,165 students being benefited from nanotechnology education.   


Conferences, Workshops, and Seminars

NVC organized and hosted a 1-day First-Ever Nanotechnology Conference in Greater San Antonio, Texas, on October 18, 2013 (over 150 attendees)&mdash;co-hosted in every year of the grant afterwards.
